Baron Davis scored 13 of his 17 points in the fourth quarter as
the Hornets handed the Cavaliers their 10th straight loss,
97-84.

Hornets center Elden Campbell has returned to
full practice for the first time since the team moved to New
Orleans and is expected to see playing time Saturday in Cleveland,
coach Paul Silas said.

article.headline: Davis shakes off back pain to lead Hornets
article.story:
CLEVELAND (AP) -- Baron Davis downplayed the back pain that kept him sidelined for the entire third quarter.
Davis

Davis scored 13 of his 17 points in the fourth quarter to lead the New Orleans Hornets to a 97-84 victory over Cleveland on Saturday night, the Cavaliers' 10th straight loss. "Just some back spasms, that's all,'' Davis said. "I got kicked in the knee in the first quarter, plus my back hurt, so I really had to shut it down. "But I love to play in the fourth. That felt great. And I should be fine for Monday night (at Philadelphia).'' David Wesley scored nine of his 20 points and Jamal Mashburn had eight of his 16 in the third quarter as the Hornets slowly added to a 47-45 halftime lead. Davis hit a 3-pointer to start the fourth, putting the Hornets ahead 77-65. "I was not going to play him at all,'' Hornets coach Paul Silas said. "He wanted to play and was mostly responsible for us breaking it open.'' New Orleans' starting backcourt of Davis and Wesley outscored the Cavs' starting guards, Bimbo Coles and Milt Palacio, 37-11, despite the Cleveland duo totaling 12 more minutes. Ricky Davis scored 24 points to lead Cleveland, including 16 in a first half that featured seven lead changes and 13 ties. Zydrunas Ilgauskas had 17 points but shot just 5-for-15 from the field. The Cavaliers made 19 of 23 free throws in the first half to stay close, but New Orleans stopped reaching in on defense in the third quarter. Cleveland went to the line just once in the quarter. "Their big fella kept getting our guys off the ground in the first half,'' Wesley said. "We tightened up the defense. That was the key.'' New Orleans, coming off an overtime win against New York on Friday night, started sluggishly. "We knew it was going to be tough coming off that,'' said Courtney Alexander, who scored 17 for the Hornets. "We just had to pick it up in the second half.'' Hornets center Elden Campbell made his season debut, but picked up three fouls in his first seven minutes. The 7-foot, 279-pound forward missed training camp with a left knee strain and had surgery in October. He practiced with the team for the first time on Wednesday. Campbell scored four points in 16 minutes. Cavs rookie Carlos Boozer had his second straight double-double with 15 points and 10 rebounds. "I've got to play the young guys,'' Cavs coach John Lucas said. "I want to win, this losing is absolutely no fun, but if I decide not to develop the young guys that's putting us even further back.'' Game notes
The Cavs (2-12) were outrebounded 50-35 without forward Tyrone Hill, who missed his second straight game with the flu. Hill is among the NBA rebound leaders, averaging 10.5 a game. ... P.J. Brown led New Orleans (10-3) with 13 rebounds. ... C DeSegana Diop, Cleveland's first-round pick in 2001, had a career-high 10 points. ... The last time the Cavs faced a New Orleans team in Cleveland was on Feb. 24, 1979, when the New Orleans Jazz won 105-96.
